#doc (Manual) "Chebotarev density theorem" =>

The general Galois case is reduced to the abelian case via the cyclic subextension
generated by a class representative. Source: Sharifi 7.2.2 Step 1 (p. 143).

:::lemma_ "lem:count-primes-above-frob-sigma" (lean := "Chebotarev.count_primes_above_with_frobenius_eq_sigma")
Let $`L/K` be a finite Galois extension with $`G = \Gal{L/K}`, $`C \subseteq G` a
conjugacy class, $`\sigma \in C`, and $`\mathfrak{p}` a nonzero prime of
$`\mathcal{O}_K` unramified in $`L` with $`\sigma_\mathfrak{p} = C`. The number of
primes $`\mathfrak{P}` of $`\mathcal{O}_L` above $`\mathfrak{p}` with
$`\Frob_\mathfrak{P} = \sigma` is exactly $`|G|/(f \cdot |C|)`, where
$`f = \operatorname{ord}(\sigma)`.

{uses "def:frobenius-at"}[] {uses "def:frobenius-class"}[]
:::

:::proof "lem:count-primes-above-frob-sigma"
The Galois group $`G` acts transitively on primes above $`\mathfrak{p}`, with
stabiliser $`D_\mathfrak{P}`. Hence the orbit has size $`|G|/|D_\mathfrak{P}|`. For
unramified $`\mathfrak{p}`, $`D_\mathfrak{P} = \langle \Frob_\mathfrak{P} \rangle`
has order $`f`, so there are $`|G|/f` primes above $`\mathfrak{p}`. Their Frobenius
elements form a $`G`-orbit in $`C` (under conjugation), which is all of $`C` by
transitivity; this orbit has size $`|C|`, and within each orbit the count of
representatives $`\sigma` is $`|G|/(f \cdot |C|)` (Sharifi p. 143).
:::

:::lemma_ "lem:density-lift-fixedfield" (lean := "Chebotarev.density_lift_through_fixedField")
Let $`\sigma \in \Gal{L/K}`, $`E = L^{\langle \sigma \rangle}`, and
$`\sigma_E \in \Gal{L/E}` the corresponding element. Given the abelian-case density
over $`E` for the Frobenius-fibre of $`\sigma_E` (value $`1/|\Gal{L/E}|`), the
$`K`-density of the Frobenius class $`[\sigma]` is $`|[\sigma]|/|G|`.

{uses "def:dirichlet-density"}[] {uses "def:frobenius-class"}[] {uses "lem:count-primes-above-frob-sigma"}[] {uses "lem:prime-ideal-sum-log"}[]
:::

:::proof "lem:density-lift-fixedfield"
For primes $`P` of $`E` above
$`\mathfrak{p} \in S = \{\mathfrak{p} : \sigma_\mathfrak{p} = [\sigma]\}`, exactly
$`|G|/(f|C|)` of the primes of $`L` above have Frobenius $`\sigma`
({bpref "lem:count-primes-above-frob-sigma"}[]); with
$`\sum_\mathfrak{p} \Norm\mathfrak{p}^{-s} \sim \sum_P \Norm{P}^{-s}`
({bpref "lem:prime-ideal-sum-log"}[] over both $`K` and $`E`),
$`\delta_K(S) = (f|C|/|G|)\,\delta_E(T_\sigma) = (f|C|/|G|)(1/f) = |C|/|G|`.

{uses "lem:count-primes-above-frob-sigma"}[] {uses "lem:prime-ideal-sum-log"}[]
:::

:::theorem "thm:chebotarev-density" (lean := "Chebotarev.chebotarev_density")
**Chebotarev density theorem.** For a finite Galois extension $`L/K` of number
fields with $`G = \Gal{L/K}` and any conjugacy class $`C \subseteq G`,
$$`\delta\bigl(\{\mathfrak{p} \subset \mathcal{O}_K : \sigma_\mathfrak{p} = C\}\bigr) \;=\; \frac{|C|}{|G|}.`

{uses "thm:chebotarev-abelian"}[] {uses "lem:density-lift-fixedfield"}[]
:::

:::proof "thm:chebotarev-density"
Pick a representative $`\sigma \in C` (`ConjClasses.mk_surjective`) and let
$`E = L^{\langle \sigma \rangle}` be the fixed field of $`\langle \sigma \rangle`.
The isomorphism $`\langle \sigma \rangle \xrightarrow{\sim} \Gal{L/E}`
(`IntermediateField.subgroupEquivAlgEquiv`) shows $`\Gal{L/E}` is commutative (as
$`\langle \sigma \rangle` is cyclic), so $`L/E` is abelian and
{bpref "thm:chebotarev-abelian"}[] applies to its Frobenius $`\sigma_E`, giving
$`\delta_E(T_\sigma) = 1/|\Gal{L/E}|`. Feeding this into the density lift
{bpref "lem:density-lift-fixedfield"}[] yields $`|C|/|G|`.

{uses "thm:chebotarev-abelian"}[] {uses "lem:density-lift-fixedfield"}[]
:::

:::theorem "thm:chebotarev-density-comm" (lean := "Chebotarev.chebotarev_density_of_comm")
**Chebotarev, abelian case.** When $`G = \Gal{L/K}` is abelian, the Chebotarev
density theorem holds: for every conjugacy class $`C`,
$`\delta(\{\mathfrak{p} : \sigma_\mathfrak{p} = C\}) = |C|/|G|`.

{uses "thm:chebotarev-abelian"}[] {uses "lem:conjclasses-carrier-card-one-comm"}[]
:::

:::proof "thm:chebotarev-density-comm"
In an abelian group each class $`C = [\sigma]` is a singleton
({bpref "lem:conjclasses-carrier-card-one-comm"}[]), so $`|C| = 1` and the target
density is $`1/|G|`; this is exactly {bpref "thm:chebotarev-abelian"}[] for the
representative $`\sigma`.

{uses "thm:chebotarev-abelian"}[] {uses "lem:conjclasses-carrier-card-one-comm"}[]
:::

# Corollaries

The corollaries below are derived directly by composition from
{bpref "thm:chebotarev-density"}[]. The Lean derivations use four small helper
sub-lemmas captured here.

:::lemma_ "lem:conjclasses-mk-one-carrier-card-one" (lean := "Chebotarev.ConjClasses_mk_one_carrier_card_eq_one")
Let $`G` be a finite group. The conjugacy class of the identity has cardinality
$`1`: $`|(\operatorname{Conj}(G))_{\{1\}}| = 1`.
:::

:::proof "lem:conjclasses-mk-one-carrier-card-one"
The carrier is $`\{1\}` (by `isConj_one_left`, $`a` is conjugate to $`1` iff
$`a = 1`); a singleton has cardinality $`1`.
:::

:::lemma_ "lem:conjclasses-carrier-card-one-comm" (lean := "Chebotarev.ConjClasses_carrier_card_eq_one_of_comm")
In a commutative finite group, every conjugacy class is a singleton, so has
cardinality $`1`.
:::

:::proof "lem:conjclasses-carrier-card-one-comm"
By `isConj_iff_eq` (conjugacy is equality in a commutative monoid), the carrier of
$`[g]` is $`\{g\}`.
:::

:::lemma_ "lem:infinite-of-density-pos" (lean := "Chebotarev.infinite_of_hasDirichletDensity_pos")
A set $`S` of prime ideals with positive Dirichlet density is infinite.
:::

:::proof "lem:infinite-of-density-pos"
Contrapositive: a finite set of primes has density $`0` by
{bpref "lem:has-density-finite"}[] (the finite case of
{bpref "def:dirichlet-density"}[]).
:::

:::lemma_ "lem:conjclasses-carrier-card-pos" (lean := "Chebotarev.ConjClasses_carrier_card_pos")
Every conjugacy class in a finite group has cardinality at least $`1` (it contains
at least its own representative).
:::

:::proof "lem:conjclasses-carrier-card-pos"
A representative $`a` with $`[a] = C` lies in the carrier (`ConjClasses.mk_surjective`
together with `mem_carrier_iff_mk_eq`), so the carrier is nonempty; a nonempty finite
set has positive cardinality.
:::

:::corollary "cor:density-split-completely" (lean := "Chebotarev.density_split_completely")
For a finite Galois extension $`L/K` of number fields, the Dirichlet density of
primes of $`\mathcal{O}_K` that split completely in $`L` equals $`1/[L:K]`.

{uses "thm:chebotarev-density"}[] {uses "lem:conjclasses-mk-one-carrier-card-one"}[]
:::

:::proof "cor:density-split-completely"
A prime $`\mathfrak{p}` splits completely in $`L` iff every
$`\mathfrak{P} \mid \mathfrak{p}` has $`\Frob_\mathfrak{P} = 1`, i.e. the Frobenius
conjugacy class is the trivial class. Apply {bpref "thm:chebotarev-density"}[] at
$`C = \operatorname{Conj}(G)_{\{1\}}`; by
{bpref "lem:conjclasses-mk-one-carrier-card-one"}[] the numerator $`|C| = 1` and by
mathlib's `IsGalois.card_aut_eq_finrank` the denominator $`|\Gal{L/K}| = [L:K]`, so
the density equals $`1/[L:K]`.

{uses "thm:chebotarev-density"}[] {uses "lem:conjclasses-mk-one-carrier-card-one"}[]
:::

:::corollary "cor:infinite-frobenius-class" (lean := "Chebotarev.infinite_setOf_frobenius_class")
For a finite Galois extension $`L/K` of number fields and any conjugacy class
$`C \subseteq \Gal{L/K}`, the set of primes $`\mathfrak{p}` of $`\mathcal{O}_K`
unramified in $`L` with Frobenius conjugacy class $`C` is infinite.

{uses "thm:chebotarev-density"}[] {uses "lem:infinite-of-density-pos"}[] {uses "lem:conjclasses-carrier-card-pos"}[]
:::

:::proof "cor:infinite-frobenius-class"
{bpref "thm:chebotarev-density"}[] gives Dirichlet density $`|C|/|G|`, which is
positive since $`|C| \ge 1` ({bpref "lem:conjclasses-carrier-card-pos"}[]) and
$`|G| \ge 1`. Apply {bpref "lem:infinite-of-density-pos"}[].

{uses "thm:chebotarev-density"}[] {uses "lem:infinite-of-density-pos"}[] {uses "lem:conjclasses-carrier-card-pos"}[]
:::

:::corollary "cor:dirichlet-ap-density" (lean := "Chebotarev.dirichlet_primes_in_AP")
**Dirichlet, density form.** For $`n \ge 1` and
$`a \in (\mathbb{Z}/n\mathbb{Z})^\times`, the Dirichlet density of the rational
primes $`p` with $`p \equiv a \pmod{n}` equals $`1/\varphi(n)`.

{uses "thm:chebotarev-density"}[]
:::

:::proof "cor:dirichlet-ap-density"
Specialise {bpref "thm:chebotarev-density"}[] to $`K = \mathbb{Q}`,
$`L = \mathbb{Q}(\zeta_n)`. The cyclotomic character identifies
$`\Gal{\mathbb{Q}(\zeta_n)/\mathbb{Q}}` with $`(\mathbb{Z}/n\mathbb{Z})^\times`; under
this identification, the Frobenius $`\sigma_p` at unramified $`p` corresponds to
$`p \bmod n`. The Galois group is abelian, so each conjugacy class is a singleton;
the set of primes with $`p \equiv a \pmod{n}` is the Frobenius preimage of $`\{a\}`,
whose density is $`1/\varphi(n)`.
:::
